APPENDIX E Determination of Depreciated Value of Buckeye's Depreciable Assets at the Cardinal Station In the event that Ohio shall elect to exercise any of the rights and options granted to it as provided in subsections (a), (b) and (c) of Section 2.8 of the Station Agreement, then Ohio and Buckeye shall cause Operating Company (or such other person as Ohio and Buckeye may designate for that purpose) to make the following determinations: A. WITH RESPECT TO BUCKEYE'S PORTION OF THE INITIAL CARDINAL STATION: 1. Determine the amount of gross investment in depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station as of June 27, 1968 and as of the end of each calendar month thereafter during the period from June 27, 1968 through the last full calendar month prior to Ohio's election to exercise the aforesaid right and option (such period being hereinafter referred to as the "computation period"). For purposes of such determination, the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station shall consist of the property and assets owned by Buckeye and located at the Initial Cardinal Station which are classified in the Production Plant Accounts, Transmission Plant Accounts and General Plant Accounts specified in the Uniform System of Accounts other than property and assets classified in Accounts 310, 350, 351 and 389 and the gross investment of Buckeye in such depreciable assets shall be the amount recorded by Buckeye in the applicable accounts of the Uniform System of Accounts in respect thereof; provided, however, that, as of June 27, 1968, the gross investment of Buckeye in depreciable assets acquired by Buckeye from Ohio shall not be less, for purposes of the computations to be made under this Item 1, than the price paid for such assets on June 27, 1968, under the Purchase Agreement, dated as of January 1, 1968 between Ohio and Buckeye (hereinafter referred to as the "Purchase Agreement"), as represented by the sum of the amounts specified in clauses (c) and (d) of the definition of the term Purchase Price Payable by Buckeye contained in the Purchase Agreement. 2. Determine for each month of the computation period the depreciation accrual applicable to the total amount of the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station by multiplying Buckeye's gross investment in such depreciable assets as of the end of the preceding month, as determined pursuant to Item 1, by 0.0025. 3. Determine the total depreciation accrual for the computation period by adding all the amounts determined on a monthly basis pursuant to Item 2. 4. Establish for each month of the computation period a ratio determined by dividing (a) 115% of Buckeye's Initial Cardinal Station Capacity Reservation in effect for the month, by (b) Buckeye's Contractual Net Capability at the Initial Cardinal Station as of the end of the month. 5. Establish for each month of the computation period a ratio determined by dividing (a) the Contract Excess Capacity for the month made available by Buckeye to Ohio from Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station prior to the Date of Commercial Operation of Buckeye's Additional Unit, by (b) Buckeye's Contractual Net Capability at the Initial Cardinal Station as of the end of such month. 6. Determine for each month of the computation period the product of the ratio for the month established pursuant to Item 4 and the gross investment in depreciable assets as of the end of the preceding month determined pursuant to Item 1. 7. Determine the depreciation accrual in dollars applicable to that part of the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station reserved for use by Buckeye in each month of the computation period by multiplying the product determined for each such month pursuant to Item 6 by 0.0025 and by adding all of the products so computed. 8. Determine for each month of the computation period the product of the ratio for the month established pursuant to Item 5 and of the gross investment in depreciable assets as of the end of the preceding month determined pursuant to Item 1. 9. Divide the computation period into semi-annual periods of six months each, beginning July 1, 1968, and determine the average investment in depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station which were made available for use by Ohio in each such semi-annual period by adding the six products computed for the six months of each such semi-annual period pursuant to Item 8 and by dividing the sum so obtained by six. The average investment in depreciable assets made available for use by Ohio in any such semi-annual period shall be hereinafter represented as In, with the subscript n representing the number of a particular semi-annual period beginning with 1 for the first such period. 10. Compute the amount of principal which would have been paid off as of the end of each semi-annual period established pursuant to Item 9 on a 35-year loan equal in amount to In in the case of the last such semi-annual period and equal in amount to In--In+ 1 in the case of each consecutively preceding semi-annual period on which, in each case, uniform semi-annual payments for principal and interest have been made on the basis of a 35-year semi-annual capital recovery factor, as shown in Column 6 under the heading "Partial Payment" in the Financial Compound Interest and Annuity Tables published by the Financial Publishing Company, Third Edition, 1961, for a rate per annum of 63/4%. The method for computing the amount of principal which would be paid off as of the end of each such semi-annual period shall be the method described in Example 39 in Section VI, page 812, of the Financial Compound Interest and Annuity Tables referred to above. 11. Determine the sum of all the amounts determined pursuant to Item 10. 12. Subtract from the sum obtained pursuant to Item 3 the total amount of the depreciation accrual determined pursuant to Item 7 and the sum determined pursuant to Item 11. 13. The depreciated value of the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Portion of the Initial Cardinal Station constituting part of the purchase price payable by Ohio to be determined as provided in subparagraph (d) of Section 2.8 of the Station Agreement shall be that amount in dollars determined by subtracting from the amount of Buckeye's gross investment in such depreciable assets at the end of the last full calendar month prior to Ohio's election to exercise its right and option under said Section 2.8 the amount of the depreciation accrual determined pursuant to Item 3 and by thereafter adding back the amount determined pursuant to Item 12. Determine for each month of the additional computation period the product of the ratio for the month established pursuant to Item 17 and the gross investment in depreciable assets as of the end of the preceding month determined pursuant to Item 14. 20. Determine the depreciation accrual in dollars applicable to that part of the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Additional Cardinal Station Facilities reserved for use by Buckeye in each month of the computation period by multiplying the product determined for each such month pursuant to Item 19 by 0.0025 and by adding all of the products so computed. 21. Determine for each month of the computation period the product of the ratio for the month established pursuant to Item 18 and of the gross investment in depreciable assets as of the end of the preceding month determined pursuant to Item 14. 22. Divide the additional computation period into semi-annual periods of six months each, beginning with the first full calendar month following the Date of Commercial Operation of Buckeye's Additional Unit, and determine the average investment in depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Additional Cardinal Station Facilities which were made available for use by Ohio in each such semi-annual period by adding the six products computed for the six months of each such semi-annual period pursuant to Item 21 and by dividing the sum so obtained by six. The average investment in depreciable assets made available for use by Ohio in any such semi-annual period shall be hereinafter represented as In, with the subscript n representing the number of a particular semi-annual period beginning with 1 for the first such period. 23. Compute the amount of principal which would have been paid off as of the end of each semi-annual period established pursuant to Item 22 on a 35-year loan equal in amount to In in the case of the last such semi-annual period and equal in amount to In-In + 1 in the case of each consecutively preceding semi-annual period on which, in each case, uniform semi-annual payments for principal and interest have been made on the basis of a 35-year semi-annual capital recovery factor, as shown in Column 6 under the heading "Partial Payment" in the Financial Compound Interest and Annuity Tables published by the Financial Publishing Company, Third Edition, 1961, for a rate per annum equal to the interest rate payable per annum on the long-term indebtedness of Buckeye Associated with Buckeye's Additional Cardinal Station Facilities and outstanding on the Date of Commercial Operation of Buckeye's Additional Unit. The method for computing the amount of principal which would be paid off as of the end of each such semi-annual period shall be the method described in Example 39 in Section VI, page 812, of the Financial Compound Interest and Annuity Tables referred to above. 24. Determine the sum of all the amounts determined pursuant to Item 23. 25. Subtract from the sum obtained pursuant to Item 16 the total amount of the depreciation accrual determined pursuant to Item 20 and the sum determined pursuant to Item 24. 26. The depreciated value of the depreciable assets included in Buckeye's Additional Cardinal Station Facilities constituting part of the purchase price payable by Ohio to be determined as provided in subparagraph (d) of Section 2.8 of the Station Agreement shall be that amount in dollars determined by subtracting from the amount of Buckeye's gross investment in such depreciable assets at the end of the last full calendar month prior to Ohio's election to exercise its right and option under said Section 2.8 the amount of the depreciation accrual determined pursuant to Item 16 and by thereafter adding back the amount determined pursuant to Item 25. In the event that Ohio shall elect to exercise any of the rights and options granted to it as provided in subsection (b) of Section 2.8 of the Station Agreement and the property, property interests and facilities to be acquired by Ohio shall include property, property interests and facilities not located at the Cardinal Station, then the depreciated value of the depreciable assets included in the property, property interests and facilities not located at the Cardinal Station shall be determined on the basis of straight line depreciation at the rate of 3% per annum from the date of acquisition thereof by Buckeye to the date of purchase thereof by Ohio from Buckeye unless a different basis for depreciation thereof shall have been agreed upon between Ohio and Buckeye prior to the election of Ohio to exercise any such right and option.

Operations and Maintenance Services Agreement Among Ohio Power Company And Trans-Allegheny Interstate Line Company
Tariff Submitter: Ohio Power Company FERC Program Name: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: OPCo RS and SA Baseline Proposed Effective Date: October 7, 2024 Tariff Record Title: OPCO-TrAILCo Kammer Operations & Maintenance Agreement Record Content Description: Rate Schedule No. 400 Option Code: A
OPERATIONS AND MAINTENANCE SERVICES AGREEMENT
This Operations and Maintenance Services Agreement (this Agreement) is entered into as of this 8th day of July, 2024 (Execution Date) between Ohio Power Company, an Ohio corporation (OPCO), and Trans-Allegheny Interstate Line Company, a West Virginia corporation (TrailCo). For purposes of this Agreement, OPCO and TrailCo shall each be referred to as a Party and collectively as the Parties.
RECITALS
A. TrailCo currently owns certain 765/500 kV transmission facilities located at the Kammer Station (the Substation) owned and operated by OPCO located in the State of West Virginia, and TrailCos facilities are more particularly described in Exhibit B (the Facilities). B. TrailCo desires OPCO to: (i) operate the Facilities, as set forth in Exhibit C to this Agreement; and (ii) maintain the Facilities, as set forth in Exhibit D to this Agreement, and OPCO is willing to operate the Facilities and maintain the Facilities in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement.
C. The Parties intend to negotiate and implement a plan to establish physically separate control buildings and to take certain other measures to physically separate the TrailCo and OPCO facilities.
AGREEMENTS
NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
1. DEFINITIONS; RULES OF CONSTRUCTION 1.1. Definitions. As used in this Agreement, terms defined in Exhibit A have the meanings set forth therein. 1.2. Rules of Construction. Unless the context of this Agreement requires otherwise, the plural includes the singular, and the singular includes the plural. The words include, includes and including are not limiting and have the inclusive meaning of including without limitation. The words hereof, herein, hereby, hereunder and other similar terms refer to this Agreement as a whole and not exclusively to any particular provision of this Agreement. All pronouns and any variations thereof will be deemed to refer to masculine, feminine, or neuter, singular, or plural, as the identity of the Person or Persons may require. Unless otherwise expressly provided, any agreement, instrument, or Applicable Law defined or referred to herein means such agreement or instrument or Applicable Law as from time to time amended, modified, or supplemented, including (in the case of agreements or instruments) by waiver or consent and (in the case of Applicable Law) by succession of comparable successor law and includes (in the case of agreements or instruments) references to all attachments thereto and instruments incorporated therein. A reference to a Party includes its successors and permitted assigns. This Agreement is the
result of negotiations between, and has been reviewed by, the Parties, and their respective counsel have had the opportunity to review this Agreement. Accordingly, this Agreement will be deemed to be the product of all Parties hereto, and no ambiguity will be construed in favor of or against any Party. 2. TERM AND TERMINATION 2.1. Effective Date and Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the date established by FERC in an order accepting this Agreement for filing (Effective Date). Subject to termination pursuant to Section 2.2, the term of this Agreement shall be five (5) years from the Effective Date (Term). The Parties shall have obligations under this Agreement, including pursuant to Section 11.1, to be performed prior to the Effective Date. 2.2. Events of Termination. Subject to the Termination Filing requirements in Section 11.1 and a FERC order accepting such Termination Filing, this Agreement may be terminated by the Parties only as follows: 2.2.1. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for an Event of Default as provided in Section 5.2; 2.2.2. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for convenience upon sixty (60) Calendar Days prior written notice to the other Party provided that the TrailCo facilities and OPCO control building are physically separated and conducive for managed communication network separation; 2.2.3. Either Party may terminate this Agreement as provided in Article 6; 2.2.4. Either Party may terminate this Agreement as provided in Section 11.1; or 2.2.5. This Agreement may be terminated by mutual written agreement of the Parties. 2.3. Effect of Termination. At the end of the Term, TrailCo shall have the right to disconnect TrailCo facilities from OPCOs communication network, but only if the TrailCo facilities and the OPCO facilities have been physically separated; OPCO shall cease performing all activities hereunder; and TrailCo shall be solely responsible for performing all such activities. 2.4. Separation of Facilities. Promptly following the Effective Date, the Parties shall reasonably coordinate to develop a plan and schedule for physical separation of the TrailCo facilities from the OPCO facilities. The Parties shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to complete the separation prior to expiration of the Term of this Agreement. 2.5. Renewal. The Parties agree that this Agreement may be renewed for an additional two (2) year term (Renewal Term), upon mutual written agreement executed by both Parties. A Party seeking to renew the Agreement shall provide the other Party with a written request to renew, no later than ninety (90) Calendar Days prior to the expiration of the Term. Any such renewal is subject to negotiation and execution of a mutually acceptable amendment to the Agreement to (a) reflect the then, current status (including, but not limited to a partial 2
physical separation of the TrailCo Facilities from the OPCO facilities) and (b) to modify the terms of the Agreement (including, but not limited to, amendments to pricing in Exhibits F and G). 2.6. ReliabilityFirst. Following execution of this Agreement, the Parties shall reasonably coordinate to have an informational meeting with ReliabilityFirst. TrailCo agrees to reimburse OPCO for any costs incurred by OPCO or its Affiliates (a) to prepare for such meeting and (b) if applicable, to respond to subsequent requests by ReliabilityFirst for additional information. 3. SERVICES 3.1. Services. 3.1.1. Operations Services. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, OPCO will perform operations services for the Facilities as set forth in Exhibit C (the Operations Services). OPCO shall provide the personnel, tools, equipment, and training that OPCO deems necessary or advisable in connection with the Operations Services. 3.1.2. Maintenance Services. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, OPCO will perform maintenance services for the Facilities as set forth in Exhibit D (the Maintenance Services). OPCO shall provide the personnel, tools, equipment, and training that OPCO deems necessary or advisable in connection with the Maintenance Services. 3.1.3. Major Repairs or Replacement; Removal. If OPCO determines that any additions, repairs or replacements that exceed $10,000.00 per event are necessary (such event being a Major Repair or Replacement), OPCO will notify TrailCo and will not perform such services unless mutually agreed by OPCO and TrailCo, except in the case of an Emergency. Unless otherwise mutually agreed by the Parties, TrailCo shall procure any necessary materials and equipment for any Major Repair or Replacement. If TrailCo does not provide its agreement for OPCO to undertake such Major Repair or Replacement, OPCO shall not have any liability under this Agreement and shall be indemnified by TrailCo pursuant to Article 9 for all damages arising out of or in connection with the failure to undertake such Major Repair or Replacement. Only TrailCo may determine whether any of the Facilities may be retired, and except in an Emergency, OPCO shall not remove any of the Facilities without the prior written approval of TrailCo. 3.1.4. Emergencies. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, if OPCO believes in good faith that a condition or circumstance that threatens imminent harm to Persons, property or the environment exists or has occurred or that the performance of any of the Operations Services or Maintenance Services would (in the reasonable judgment of OPCO) create an unreasonable safety risk to Persons, property, or the environment, or would violate the safety policies or procedures of OPCO or any OPCO Resources (each of the foregoing, an Emergency), OPCO may take such actions, or cause such actions to be taken, that, in OPCOs sole 3
judgment, are reasonably required to avoid or mitigate the Emergency without the need for prior notice to or approval by TrailCo; provided, however, that OPCO shall promptly notify TrailCo after such actions are taken. 3.1.5. Scope Limitation. TrailCo agrees that OPCOs responsibilities with respect to Operations Services and Maintenance Services are limited to those set forth in Exhibit C and Exhibit D. 3.1.6. Changes to Scope. The Parties may amend the scope of the Operations Services or the Maintenance Services pursuant to an amendment of this Agreement under Section 11.4. 3.2. Standards of Performance. OPCO shall perform the Operations Services and Maintenance Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Law. Subject to the foregoing, OPCO shall perform the Operations Services and Maintenance Services in accordance with the same standards and procedures it utilizes to perform such services on its own facilities. 3.3. Use of Resources. OPCO may perform the Operations Services and Maintenance Services under this Agreement by using subcontractors, suppliers, consultants, and personnel from its Affiliates (collectively, the OPCO Resources). OPCO will be solely responsible for the supervision, direction, and control of all of the OPCO Resources engaged in the performance of the Operations Services and Maintenance Services and such personnel will be deemed to be the employees or independent contractors of OPCO and not of TrailCo. As between OPCO and TrailCo, OPCO will be responsible for the payment of all compensation, benefits, and employment taxes with respect to the services provided by the OPCO Resources. OPCO will have the right to remove, reassign, or take any other employment-related action in regard to any of the OPCO Resources. OPCO shall cause each OPCO Resource performing the Operations Services or Maintenance Services under this Agreement to comply with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, but only OPCO shall be liable under this Agreement for the performance of the obligations under this Agreement regardless of OPCOs reliance on the OPCO Resources. 3.4. Cooperation. TrailCo will coordinate its activities with respect to the Facilities with those of OPCO and the OPCO Resources and will generally cooperate with all such parties so as to minimize delays, errors, inconsistencies, changes, and unnecessary costs to perform the Operations Services and Maintenance Services; provided, however, that TrailCo shall not be obligated to act contrary to Good Utility Practice or Applicable Law in providing such cooperation. 3.5. Access. TrailCo grants OPCO and the OPCO Resources access rights to the Facilities and the use of and the right to occupy such physical space associated with the Facilities, at all times during the Term and Renewal Term, if applicable, as may be reasonably necessary or convenient to OPCO to perform the Operations Services or Maintenance Services. 3.6. TrailCo Written Instructions. At any time, OPCO may, if it deems it to be reasonably necessary or appropriate, request and receive detailed written instructions (or clarifications of directives) from TrailCo prior to taking any action with respect to the Operations 4
Services or Maintenance Services. OPCO may defer action pending the receipt of such written instructions. TrailCo agrees that it will not unreasonably withhold or delay any written instruction or direction to OPCO that is necessary to enable OPCO to provide the Operations Services or Maintenance Services. 3.7. Compliance with Reliability Standards. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, each Party will perform the activities associated with the applicable Reliability Standards specified in Exhibit E (Applicable Reliability Standards) for the Facilities. OPCO agrees to provide supporting data and information to TrailCo or PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM), as appropriate, necessary for TrailCo to meet its obligations with respect to the Applicable Reliability Standards for the Facilities. TrailCo accepts that OPCO will perform its Operations Services and Maintenance Services in accordance with the compliance practices of OPCO and its Affiliates. OPCO is not required to make any compliance registration filings with NERC, a Regional Entity, or any other Governmental Authority on behalf of TrailCo with respect to the Facilities. TrailCo acknowledges and agrees TrailCo shall include the Facilities as assets listed as a part of TrailCos NERC or Regional Entity audit and compliance plans and obligations, and will not be included or listed in any of OPCO or its Affiliates NERC or Regional Entity audit and compliance plans and obligations associated with non-CIP (i.e. operations and planning) NERC reliability standards. TrailCo cyber assets associated with the Facilities will be included and listed in any of OPCOs or its Affiliates NERC or Regional Entity audit and compliance plans and obligations related to the CIP family of reliability standards. 3.8. Responsibility for Non-Compliance. For the avoidance of doubt and notwithstanding any other terms of this Agreement, neither OPCO nor any of its Affiliates shall be responsible for any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with the Applicable Reliability Standards imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Facilities except with respect to OPCOs gross negligence or willful misconduct consistent with Section 9.1. 3.9. Acknowledgement Regarding Compliance. TrailCo acknowledges and agrees that by entering into this Agreement, neither OPCO nor any of its Affiliates assume any responsibility or accountability on behalf of TrailCo for past compliance failures or remedial or enforcement actions (including any penalty or fine) related to the Facilities. 3.10. Meetings. Representatives from OPCO and TrailCo shall meet periodically but not less than once per year. TrailCo will schedule the meetings at times and locations that are mutually agreeable to both OPCO and TrailCo. TrailCo will facilitate the meetings between the Parties and distribute a proposed meeting agenda no less than two weeks in advance of the meeting. TrailCo shall issue meeting minutes to all attendees summarizing the discussion and any resolved or pending action items. The meeting shall be governed by the requirements of the FERC Standards of Conduct. The meetings will include a review, at a minimum, of the following topics: 5
3.10.1. Status of implementation of plans to separate TrailCo and OPCO facilities in order for TrailCo to perform all services for its Facilities set forth in Exhibit C and Exhibit D. 3.10.2. Unscheduled Substation service outages due to switchyard or grid events; 3.10.3. Transmission system modifications that impact the capability (loading/lines/fault capability) of the Substation; 3.10.4. OPCO modifications that impact the Substation; 3.10.5. Updates on the status of scheduled/pending, completed and backlogged work that OPCO is responsible for at the Substation; 3.10.6. A general health assessment of the TrailCo Facilities. 3.10.7. Yearly estimated costs for any scheduled work. 3.10.8. Review and update the OPCO and TrailCo personnel contact lists; and 3.10.9. Any additional concerns regarding engineering, budgetary, or regulatory compliance issues between OPCO and TrailCo. 3.11. TrailCo Conditions. OPCO will not have any liability for failure to perform under this Agreement to the extent such failure is attributable to TrailCo not performing its obligations in material compliance with the requirements of this Agreement. 4. COSTS; INVOICING; TAXES 4.1. Responsibility for Costs. 4.1.1. TrailCo shall reimburse OPCO for its costs to perform the Operations Services through monthly charges set forth in Exhibit F. OPCOs costs to perform the Operations Services shall be determined as follows: (a) OPCOs costs to perform the Operations Services under this Agreement will include all costs, charges, and expenses reasonably incurred by OPCO in connection with the Operations Services, including: the costs of materials, facilities, services, and supplies from third parties; the costs of materials and facilities withdrawn from OPCOs internal inventories (or those of its Affiliates); transportation and storage costs; internal payroll and payroll loading factors; travel expenses; overhead factors; other internal costs; the costs to acquire land rights; third-party expenses; sales and use taxes; and fees and costs for Governmental Approvals. (b) Within sixty (60) Calendar Days after the Effective Date, OPCO shall provide TrailCo with an estimate of the total amount of costs for the Maintenance Services for the remainder of 2024. Thereafter, on or before 6
December 1 of each year, OPCO shall provide TrailCo with an estimate of the costs for the Maintenance Services for the following calendar year. 4.1.2. TrailCo shall reimburse OPCO for its costs to perform the Maintenance Services through the formula set forth in Exhibit G. 4.1.3. TrailCo will be responsible for all capital costs associated with the Facilities, including replacement of failed major components. 4.1.4. All commercially reasonable and verifiable costs incurred for all actions taken by OPCO or OPCO Resources to avoid or mitigate an Emergency in regard to the Facilities in accordance with Section 3.1.4 will be paid or reimbursed by TrailCo. 4.2. Information Concerning Costs. On reasonable advance written notice, TrailCo will have the right to examine the pertinent records of OPCO as reasonably necessary to verify that costs invoiced pursuant to this Agreement were incurred in accordance with this Agreement. Any such examination will be conducted during regular business hours at the OPCO offices and shall be conducted in a manner that does not unreasonably interfere with OPCOs business or operations. TrailCo will not have the right to examine the records pertaining to an invoice unless written notice of the examination is given within three (3) months of the date of such invoice. OPCO shall not be obligated to provide TrailCo with access or any other rights to information to the extent such information is: (a) otherwise restricted from disclosure by OPCO; or (b) privileged (e.g., pursuant to attorney-client privilege or work-product protection). Information obtained by TrailCo from OPCO pursuant to this section will be considered OPCOs Confidential Information pursuant to Article 10 regardless of whether such information is identified as confidential. 4.3. Invoices. 4.3.1. Not later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the end of each month during the Term and Renewal Term, if applicable, OPCO will deliver to TrailCo an invoice which will show the charges payable by TrailCo for the month, and payment will be made by TrailCo no later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the date the invoice is received by TrailCo. Invoices issued to TrailCo should be submitted to kammerinvoice@firstenergycorp.com. 4.3.2. If TrailCo disputes any portion of any amount specified in an invoice delivered by OPCO, TrailCo will pay the undisputed amount of the invoice when due, and TrailCo shall state the basis for disputing part of the invoice amount. If it is determined that an overpayment or underpayment has been made by TrailCo or the amount charged on an invoice is incorrect, then: (a) in the case of any overpayment by TrailCo, OPCO will promptly return the amount of the overpayment (or credit the amount of the overpayment on the next invoice) to TrailCo; or (b) in the case of an underpayment by TrailCo, TrailCo will promptly pay the amount of the underpayment to OPCO (no later than the due date of the next invoice). In each case, payment will be made together with interest at the Default Rate for the period from the date of overpayment or underpayment, until such amount has been paid or credited against a future invoice. 7
4.4. Tax Treatment of Costs. The amounts TrailCo agrees to pay OPCO pursuant to Section 4.1 of this Agreement are exclusive of any state or local sales or use tax, or any other tax or similar charge. If OPCO is required by Applicable Law to pay or collect any such tax, or if TrailCo is required to withhold such tax, then such amount will be paid or reimbursed to OPCO by TrailCo. TrailCo shall not be responsible to pay any federal, state, or local tax imposed on OPCO and related to OPCOs receipt of monies under this Agreement. 5. DEFAULT; REMEDIES 5.1. Events of Default. An Event of Default will exist: 5.1.1. as to TrailCo, upon TrailCos failure to promptly pay any amount due under this Agreement within ten (10) Calendar Days following written notice of delinquency describing such failure in reasonable detail; 5.1.2. as to a Party, if that Party fails to commence the cure of its breach of any other obligation under this Agreement within thirty (30) Calendar Days following written notification of such breach in reasonable detail; provided that, if such failure is not capable of being cured within such thirty (30) Calendar Day period despite diligent efforts, then such thirty (30) Calendar Day period will be extended for such period as may be reasonably necessary to complete such cure with diligent efforts if the defaulting Party commences its cure within the initial thirty (30) Calendar Day period and thereafter prosecutes its cure diligently to completion; or 5.1.3. if a Party files a voluntary petition of bankruptcy or is adjudged bankrupt or insolvent or has entered against it an order for relief, in any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding. 5.2. Termination. If an Event of Default occurs as to a Party described in Sections 5.1.1 or 5.1.2, then the other Party will have the right to terminate this Agreement by written notice to the defaulting Party, subject to the Termination Filing provisions in Section 11.1 and a FERC order accepting such Termination Filing. Upon an Event of Default by a Party described in Section 5.1.3, the other Party may terminate this Agreement with immediate effect by written notice to the defaulting Party, subject to the Termination Filing provisions in Section 11.1 and a FERC order accepting such Termination Filing. 5.3. Other remedies. 5.3.1. If an Event of Default occurs and while it persists with respect to a Party, the other Party may suspend performance of its obligations under this Agreement (other than its obligations to pay money for services provided) without prejudice to any other remedy that it may have under this Agreement or Applicable Law. 5.3.2. Whether or not a Party suspends performance of its obligations under, or terminates, this Agreement as a result of an Event of Default, TrailCo will pay all amounts due, if any, for Operations Services and Maintenance Services provided and, if applicable, a Party shall pay all amounts due for indemnification under Article 9. 8
5.3.3. Subject to the limitations in Section 3.8 and Article 8 and the indemnification obligations of Article 9, TrailCo will be entitled to recover direct contract damages from OPCO as a result of an Event of Default (Allowable Damages). Except as provided in this Section 5.3.3, the only other remedies for an Event of Default by OPCO are either re-performance in accordance with Article 7 or termination pursuant to Section 5.2. 6. FORCE MAJEURE Neither Party will be responsible for any delay or failure to perform hereunder (other than any obligation to pay money) if such delay or failure to perform is attributable to an event of Force Majeure. In such event, the performance so affected by the Force Majeure event will be extended by a period of time corresponding to the period of time such Force Majeure event exists. In the event of an occurrence of Force Majeure, the non-performing Party shall provide written notice to the other Party within ten (10) Calendar Days after the occurrence of the Force Majeure event. The non-performing Party will use good faith efforts to attempt, in a commercially reasonable manner, to rectify the conditions brought about by the Force Majeure and to avoid or minimize delay. Neither Party will be required by this Agreement to settle any strike, walkout, lockout, or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the Party involved in the dispute, are contrary to its interest, it being understood that the settlement of strikes, walkouts, lockouts, or other labor disputes will be at the sole discretion of the Party having the difficulty. Either Party will have the right to terminate this Agreement if a Force Majeure event prevents performance for more than ninety (90) Calendar Days. 7. DISCLAIMER OF WARRANTIES THE REMEDIES CONTAINED IN THIS ARTICLE 7 AND ARTICLE 5 ARE TRAILCOS EXCLUSIVE REMEDIES, AND THEY ARE GIVEN AND ACCEPTED IN LIEU OF (A) ANY EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES BY OPCO, INCLUDING WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR GOOD AND WORKMANLIKE PERFORMANCE, AND (B) ANY OBLIGATION, LIABILITY, RIGHT, CLAIM OR REMEDY AT LAW OR IN EQUITY ARISING OUT OF ANY DEFECT IN THE SERVICES WHETHER SUCH CLAIM ARISES UNDER CONTRACT, TORT, STRICT LIABILITY, STATUTE OR ANY OTHER LEGAL OR EQUITABLE THEORY OR PRINCIPLE INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE, GROSS NEGLIGENCE, OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT. WITH RESPECT TO ANY DEFECT IN THE SERVICES RESULTING FROM THE GROSS NEGLIGENCE OR INTENTIONAL MISCONDUCT OF OPCO, TRAILCO MAY DIRECT THAT THOSE SERVICES BE RE-PERFORMED AT OPCOs SOLE COST AND EXPENSE. 8. LIMITATION OF OPCOS LIABILITY; EXCLUSION OF CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES 8.1. Limitation of OPCOs Liability. Except as set forth in Section 3.8, OPCOs aggregate liability for all Allowable Damages, if any, for breach of its obligations under this Agreement related to Operations Services or Maintenance Services rendered during any 9
Contract Year will not exceed the excess of (a) all amounts billed by OPCO for the Operations Services and Maintenance Services rendered during the preceding Contract Year (or, where such services were rendered in the first Contract Year, during that first Contract Year) over (b) all amounts paid or payable (including taxes and other associated costs) by OPCO for materials or equipment incorporated into the work in the course of the Operations Services and Maintenance Services in that preceding Contract Year (or, where such services were rendered in the first Contract Year, during the first Contract Year); provided, however, that OPCOs liability to TrailCo shall not be limited as set forth in this Section 8.1 to the extent the Allowable Damages arise from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of OPCO or its officers, employees, agents, or subcontractors. 8.2. Exclusion of Consequential Damages. Neither Party will be liable under this Agreement for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, punitive, or exemplary damages in any action arising out of this Agreement, whether based on contract, tort, or any other theory of liability. The preceding limitation of liability shall not apply to the extent such damages are claimed by a third party for which the Indemnifying Person has an obligation of indemnification to an Indemnified Person under Article 9 of this Agreement. 9. INDEMNIFICATION 9.1. Indemnification for Third-Party Losses. 9.1.1. TrailCo shall be liable to and shall indemnify, hold harmless, and defend OPCO, its Affiliates, and its or their directors, managers, officers, employees, contractors, consultants, and agents (each an OPCO Indemnified Person) for any third-party Losses, including personal injury (including death) suffered by any third party or damage to a third partys tangible property; penalties or compliance costs imposed on OPCO or its Affiliates by any Governmental Authority, including NERC, with respect to the Facilities; reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense; and (with the approval of TrailCo) costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the OPCO Indemnified Person, arising in connection with the ownership, operation, or maintenance of the Facilities or TrailCos performance, or failure to perform, under this Agreement, except to the extent such Losses are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of an OPCO Indemnified Person. 9.1.2. OPCO shall be liable to and shall indemnify, hold harmless, and defend TrailCo, its Affiliates, and its or their directors, managers, officers, employees and agents (each a TrailCo Indemnified Person) for any third-party Losses, including personal injury (including death) suffered by any third party or damage to a third partys tangible property, reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and (with the approval of OPCO) costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the TrailCo Indemnified Person, arising in connection with OPCOs performance of, or failure to perform, its Operations Services and Maintenance Services obligations under this Agreement, but only to the extent such Losses are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of an OPCO Indemnified Person. 10
9.2. Notice Procedure. Each OPCO Indemnified Person or TrailCo Indemnified Person (individually, Indemnified Person), as applicable, must provide prompt notice of any Losses for which it seeks indemnity under this provision and cooperate in defense of such Losses. Without the consent of the applicable Indemnified Persons, an Indemnifying Person may not settle any such claim for any relief (other than monetary damages) or any claim in the nature of regulatory or similar legal enforcement action by a Governmental Authority. 9.3. FORMULA RATE FOR MAINTENANCE SERVICES
A. General
The formula rate contained in this Exhibit G applies when OPCO performs Maintenance Services for non-OPCO parties. OPCO will recover costs for the performance of Maintenance Services through invoices that reflect the costs OPCO incurred in the following six categories, namely: (1) materials; (2) labor; (3) equipment; (4) outside services; (5) engineering and administration; and (6) taxes.
OPCO charges its costs for Maintenance Services on behalf of others to special work orders that accumulate the costs to be billed. As a result of these accounting procedures, the charges billed to non-OPCO parties are not reflected in OPCOs transmission, operation, maintenance, or plant accounts.
The types of costs that OPCO incurs and bills are the types of costs that would be assignable to the following FERC Uniform System of Accounts if they were incurred in connection with OPCOs own property:
Operation and Maintenance - Transmission Operation and Maintenance Expenses

352 - Structures and Improvements 353 - Station Equipment 397 - Communications Equipment 108 - Accumulated Provision for Depreciation

Exhibit G Page 1 The charges billed for Maintenance Services in each of the previously identified six categories are discussed in order below.
When invoicing for Maintenance Services, OPCO agrees to provide TrailCo reasonably sufficient detail so that the total charges assessed are identified per the six cost categories described below.
1. Materials
Materials charges are made in four sub-categories: (1) direct material costs (DM), which may be (a) delivered direct from vendors to the job site (VDM), or (b) issued from company stores (SDM); (2) purchasing expenses (PE); (3) stores expenses (SE); and (4) exempt minor materials (EM). The latter three costs are charged using material loading rates described below.
DM costs are vendor invoiced charges for items, other than exempt minor materials, which are used for maintenance. PE are material overhead costs incurred in selecting and ordering materials. SE are the costs of performing the stores function. EM are low cost expendable materials, supplies, and hand tools used in transmission operation and maintenance.
VDM are charged at cost, plus a purchasing loading rate (plr) of 1%, up to a maximum of $150 per invoice. SDM are charged at cost, plus a combined stores/purchasing loading rate (slr) and an EM loading rate (mlr).
Projected annual SE and EM costs are divided by projected annual costs of stores issued materials (SDM + EM) to determine projected SE and EM loading rates. The rates are reviewed monthly and adjusted as required to clear current year SE and EM costs to the accounts charged with the materials issued.
In symbolic format, the charges for materials are calculated as follows:
M = DM + [VDM x (plr), up to $150/bill] + SDM x (1 + (mlr)) x (slr)
2. Labor
Labor is charged to maintenance work orders in three parts - direct labor (DL), fringe labor costs (FL), and miscellaneous out-of-pocket employee expenses (ME). DL charges reflect the actual work hours (whr) and basic hourly rates of pay (hrp) for the personnel that are directly involved; i.e., DL = (whr) x (hrp). FL costs (such as vacation, holiday, sick leave, and other paid time away, plus payroll taxes, insurance, workers compensation, pension, and savings plan expenses) are recovered through labor loading rates (llr) that are developed by dividing FL earned payroll. The llr are reviewed monthly and adjusted, as needed, to clear FL costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the charges for labor are calculated as follows:
L = DL + FL + ME = DL x (1 + llr) + ME
Exhibit G Page 2 3. Equipment
Equipment (E), primarily vehicles, used in the performance of maintenance is charged based on actual hours of usage (aeu) and hourly equipment cost rates (ecr). Costs of purchasing, leasing, and operating equipment, by equipment class, are collected in clearing accounts and divided by total hours of usage by class to develop the E cost rates. E cost rates are reviewed quarterly and adjusted, as needed, to clear the cost of E.
In symbolic format, E charges are calculated as follows:
E = (aeu) x (ecr)
4. Outside Services
The actual amount of invoices received from vendors for restorative and other maintenance services (S) performed by third parties for OPCO is charged in maintenance billings by OPCO.
5. Engineering and Administration
Engineering and administrative overhead loading rates are used to allocate engineering, supervision, and administrative overhead costs not assigned to specific project work orders. OPCO uses separate loading rates for American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEPSC) engineering (SCEt&d) and construction overhead costs (CCO).
As the description of Construction Overhead Procedure in Section 1.B below shows, the CCO and SCEt&d loading rates (cclr and sclrt&d, respectively) are derived in the normal course of business for the purpose of capturing the portions of AEPSC engineering and operating company construction overhead costs which are incurred in connection with transmission and distribution plan construction. The cclr and sclrt&d are reviewed monthly and updated, as needed, to clear the respective engineering and administrative overhead costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the engineering and administration overhead costs (O) are calculated as follows:
O = CCO + SCEt&d
Where CCO = (M + L + E + S) x cclr
and SCEt&d = (M + L + E + S + CCO) x sclrt&d
6. Taxes
The total taxes charged to TrailCo will be the sum of receipts (RT) and other taxes incurred (OT).
i.e.: T = RT + OT
